\"| [[2001 NBA playoffs|2001]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2000\u201301 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio]]\n| 13 || 13 || 31.5 || .472 || .000 || .695 || 11.8 || 1.7 || 1.3 || 2.4 || 16.6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2002 NBA playoffs|2002]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2001\u201302 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio]]\n| 4 || 4 || 20.3 || .474 || .000 || .000 || 5.8\t || 1.3 || .8 || .8 || 4.5 \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:#afe6ba;\"| [[2003 NBA playoffs|2003]]\u2020 \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2002\u201303 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio]]\n| '''23''' || '''23''' || 23.4 || .542 || .000 || .667 || 6.6 || .9 || .8 || 1.3 || 7.8\n|-\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=2| Career\n| 123 || 123 || 34.3 || .479 || .100 || .708 || 10.6 || 2.3 || 1.2 || 2.5 || 18.1\n{{S-end}}\n\n==National team career==\n[[File:Dream Team at the 1992 Summer Olympics.JPEG|thumb|left|Robinson at the free throw line in 1992 for the \u201cDream Team\u201d]]\nDavid Robinson was a member of the [[United States men's national basketball team|United States national team]] at the [[1986 FIBA World Championship]], the [[1987 Pan American Games]], the [[1988 Summer Olympics]], [[1992 Summer Olympics]], and the [[1996 Summer Olympics]]. He won the gold medal at all games except the 1987 Pan Am Games, where he won a silver medal, and the 1988 Summer Olympics, where he won a bronze medal.\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:David Robinson 13636-0427.jpg|thumb|Robinson at the LBJ Presidential Library in 2014]]\nRobinson married Valerie Hoggatt in 1991. They have three sons, David Jr., Corey, and Justin. [[Corey Robinson (wide receiver)|Corey]] attended [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]] and was a wide receiver on the [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|football team]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irish.nbcsports.com/2013/02/05/early-enrollees-corey-robinson/|title=Early Enrollees: Corey Robinson|first=Keith|last=Arnold|date=February 5, 2013}}</ref> before ending his playing career in 2016 on medical advice due to multiple [[concussion]]s prior to what would have been his senior season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/sports/blogs/ncaaf-dr-saturday/notre-dame-wr-corey-robinson-medically-retires-due-to-concussions-223802086.html |title=Notre Dame WR Corey Robinson medically retires due to concussions |first=Nick |last=Bromberg |work=Dr. Saturday |publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |date=June 15, 2016 |accessdate=June 16, 2016}}</ref> He was very active on campus in his final undergraduate year, having been elected student body president in February 2016 for the 2016\u201317 school year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/ncaaf-dr-saturday/notre-dame-wr-corey-robinson-wins-student-body-president-election-144250730.html |title=Notre Dame WR Corey Robinson wins student body president election |first=Nick |last=Bromberg |work=Dr. Saturday |publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |date=February 11, 2016 |accessdate=June 16, 2016}}</ref> Justin, a 6'8\" (2.03 m) forward in basketball and a two-time all-state selection in Texas, has attended [[Duke University|Duke]] since August 2015. He was initially [[College recruiting|recruited]] to the [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke team]] as a \"preferred [[Walk-on (sports)|walk-on]]\" with the opportunity to eventually earn a [[Athletic scholarship|scholarship]], but was placed on scholarship before his arrival at Duke.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://collegebasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/05/06/son-of-former-nba-great-david-robinson-to-be-on-scholarship-at-duke-next-season/ |title=Son of former NBA great David Robinson to be on scholarship at Duke next season |first=Raphielle |last=Johnson |series=College Basketball Talk |work=[[NBC Sports]] |date=May 6, 2015 |accessdate=May 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRobinson became a [[Christianity|Christian]] on June 8, 1991 after being encouraged to read the [[Bible]].<ref name=\"Leigh Montville\">{{cite news|author=Leigh Montville |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1008057/index.htm |title=SAN ANTONIO SPURS CENTER AND BORN AGAIN CHRISTIAN DAVID \u2013 04.29.96 \u2013 SI Vault |work=Sports Illustrated|date=April 29, 1996 |accessdate=August 4, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Leigh Montville\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Joshua Cooley |url=https://www.focusonthefamily.com/parenting/parenting-roles/david-robinson-parenting-in-the-fourth-quarter |title=David Robinson: Parenting in the Fourth Quarter |work=Focus on the Family |date=March\u2013April 2013 |accessdate=January 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Robinson founded and funded the $9&nbsp;million [[Carver Academy]] in San Antonio, a non-profit private school named for [[George Washington Carver]] to provide more opportunities for inner-city children. In 2012, the school became a public charter school and its name changed to IDEA Carver. Robinson continues to be a very active participant in the school's day-to-day activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/sports/2013/05/the-25-smartest-athlete-purchases-in-sports-history/|title=The 25 Smartest Athlete Purchases in Sports History17. David Robinson Builds Carver Academy|website=Complex}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ksat.com/news/david-robinson-gives-idea-carver-academy-kids-shopping-spree/-/478452/20505320/-/wgkg5iz/-/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131027124855/http://www.ksat.com/news/david-robinson-gives-idea-carver-academy-kids-shopping-spree/-/478452/20505320/-/wgkg5iz/-/index.html|url-status=dead|title=David Robinson gives IDEA Carver Academy kids shopping spree|archivedate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Robinson earned a Master of Arts in Administration (with concentration in organizational development) from the [[University of the Incarnate Word]] to better \"understand how businesses work and how to build them.\".<ref name=\"sanantoniomag.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sanantoniomag.com/SAM/March-2012/The-Education-of-David-Robinson/|title=The Education of David Robinson - San Antonio Magazine - March 2012 - San Antonio, TX|website=www.sanantoniomag.com}}</ref>\n\nBeyond his founding of Carver Academy, Robinson is well known as a [[philanthropy|philanthropist]]. Robinson and business partner Daniel Bassichis donate 10 percent of their profits to charitable causes.<ref name=\"sanantoniomag.com\"/> The winner of the [[NBA Community Assist Award]] is presented with the David Robinson Plaque.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/spurs/features/robinson_hof_community.html|title=David Robinson: Impact on the Community|website=San Antonio Spurs}}</ref>\n\n===Other ventures===\n\nIn 2008 Robinson partnered with Daniel Bassichis, formerly of [[Goldman Sachs]] and a board member of The Carver Academy, to form Admiral Capital Group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://admiralcapitalgroup.com/founders.php |title=Admiral Capital Group |publisher=Admiral Capital Group |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2012}}</ref> Admiral Capital Group is a private equity firm whose mission is to invest in opportunities that can provide both financial and social returns. Robinson's primary motivation in starting Admiral Capital was to create a source of additional financial support for The Carver Academy. Its portfolio is worth more than $100&nbsp;million and includes nine upscale hotels and office buildings across the U.S. as well as Centerplate, one of the largest hospitality companies in the world. Admiral Capital Group also partnered with Living Cities to form the Admiral Center, a non-profit created to support other athletes and entertainers with their philanthropic initiatives. Robinson is also co-owner of a Jaguar Land Rover Dealership in San Juan, Texas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.admiralcapitalgroup.com/history.php|title=Home Page - Admiral Capital Group|website=Admiral Capital Group}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jaguarsanjuantx.com/dealership/about.htm|title=ABOUT US &#124; Jaguar San Juan Texas|first=Jaguar San Juan|last=Texas|website=www.jaguarsanjuantx.com}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Naismith Basketball Hall of Fame]]\n**class of 2009 \u2013 individual\n**class of 2010 \u2013 as a member of the \"Dream Team\"\n*[[U.S. Olympic Hall of Fame]]\n**class of 2008 \u2013 individual\n**class of 2009 \u2013 as a member of the \"Dream Team\"\n*[[FIBA Hall of Fame]]\n**class of 2013 - individual\n**class of 2017 - as a member of the \"Dream Team\"\n*Two-time NBA Champion \n*1995 NBA MVP \n*1992 NBA Defensive Player of the Year \n*1990 NBA Rookie of the Year \n*1990 [[NBA All-Rookie First Team]]\n*Four-time All-NBA First Team \n*Four-time All-Defensive First Team \n*10-time NBA All-Star\n* 2001 [[NBA Sportsmanship Award]]<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2013/04/30/nba-sportsmanship-award-winners/ | work=Fox News | title=NBA Sportsmanship Award Winners | date=April 30, 2013}}</ref>\n*Two-time [[Olympic Gold Medal]] winner \n*Olympic Bronze Medal winner \n*One of 50 Greatest Players in NBA History \n*1994 NBA Scoring Champion\n*Five-time [[IBM Award]] winner<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2000/04/27/shap000426.html Shaq claims NBA's IBM award]</ref>\n*2008 [[NBA Shooting Stars]] champion<ref>{{cite web|title=NBA All-Star Shooting Stars Winners|date=August 24, 2017|website=NBA.com|url=http://www.nba.com/history/all-star/shooting-stars#/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224155543/http://www.nba.com/history/all-star/shooting-stars|archivedate=February 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Gold Medal in [[1986 FIBA World Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usabasketball.com/history/mwc_1986.html|title=1986 USA Basketball|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814002049/http://www.usabasketball.com/history/mwc_1986.html|archivedate=August 14, 2007}}</ref>\n* 2003 [[Sportsman of the Year|''Sports Illustrated'' Sportsman of the Year]] \n*2012 NCAA Silver Anniversary Award<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ncaa.org/wps/wcm/connect/public/ncaa/resources/latest+news/2012/january/former+ncaa+stars+shine+at+honors+celebration |title=Former NCAA stars shine at Honors Celebration |publisher=NCAA.org |date=January 13, 2012 |accessdate=August 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523041706/http://www.ncaa.org/wps/wcm/connect/public/ncaa/resources/latest%2Bnews/2012/january/former%2Bncaa%2Bstars%2Bshine%2Bat%2Bhonors%2Bcelebration |archivedate=May 23, 2012 }}</ref>\n*Number 50 retired by the San Antonio Spurs\n* [[Coach Wooden \"Keys to Life\" Award]] (2004)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==NBA records==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=August 2019}}\n\n====Regular season====\n'''Fourth (and most recent) player in NBA history to record a [[quadruple-double]] in a game''': San Antonio Spurs (115) vs. Detroit Pistons (96), {{Dts|1994|2|17}}\n*34 points, 10 rebounds, 10 assists, 10 blocked shots (and 2 steals) in 43 minutes\n* [[Nate Thurmond]], [[Alvin Robertson]] and [[Hakeem Olajuwon]] are the only other players to achieve this.\n\n'''Fourth player in NBA history to score 70 or more points in a game''': 71, at Los Angeles Clippers, {{Dts|1994|April|24|format=mdy}}\n* [[Elgin Baylor]], [[Wilt Chamberlain]] and [[David Thompson (basketball)|David Thompson]] also achieved this. [[Kobe Bryant]] and [[Devin Booker]] have achieved this since then.\n\n'''One of two players in NBA history to lead the league in scoring ({{nbay|1993}}), rebounding ({{nbay|1990}}) and blocked shots ({{nbay|1991}}) during his career'''\n* [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]] was the first player to achieve this.\n*Hakeem Olajuwon led the league in blocks three times, and in rebounding twice, but the closest he came to a scoring title was second place, both in {{nbay|1994}} (Shaquille O'Neal) and {{nbay|1995}} (Michael Jordan).\n\n'''Second player in NBA history to win Rookie of the Year, Defensive Player of the Year and Most Valuable Player during his career'''\n* [[Michael Jordan]] was the first player to achieve this.\n* [[Hakeem Olajuwon]] won Defensive Player of the Year and Most Valuable Player during his career, but finished second in Rookie of the Year voting to Jordan in {{nbay|1984}}.\n\n'''Only player in NBA history to lead the league in scoring, rebounding, and blocked shots and win awards for Rookie of the Year, Defensive Player of the Year and Most Valuable Player during his career'''\n*Kareem Abdul-Jabbar achieved all of these except for Defensive Player of the Year, an award which did not exist for most of his career.\n\n'''Only player in NBA history to rank among top five players in the league in rebounding, blocks and steals in the same season''': {{nbay|1991}}\n*Ranked first in blocks (4.49 bpg), fourth in rebounding (12.2 rpg) and fifth in steals (2.32 spg).\n*Hakeem Olajuwon ranked first in rebounding, fourth in blocks and sixth in steals in {{nbay|1988}}.\n\n'''Only player in NBA history to rank among the top seven players in the league in five statistics in the same season''': {{nbay|1991}}\n*Ranked seventh in scoring (23.2 ppg), fourth in rebounding (12.2 rpg), first in blocks (4.49 bpg), fifth in steals (2.32 spg) and seventh in [[field-goal percentage]] (.551)\n\n===Playoffs===\n'''Highest field goal percentage in a game (minimum 8 made)''': 1.000 (8\u20148), vs. Phoenix Suns, {{Dts|2003|4|19}} (OT)\n*Tied with many other players\n\n'''Part of second trio of players in NBA history to score 30 or more points in the same game''': San Antonio Spurs (130) vs. Golden State Warriors (121), {{Dts|1991|4|25}}\n* [[Willie Anderson (basketball)|Willie Anderson]]: 38 points\n* [[Rod Strickland]]: 30 points\n*Robinson: 30 points\n\n===All-Star===\n'''Personal fouls, quarter''': 4 ([[1991 NBA All-Star Game|1991]])\n\n==Charitable efforts==\nIn addition to his lengthy NBA career, Robinson is also noted for his charitable work.\n\nIn 1991, Robinson visited with fifth graders at Gates Elementary School in [[San Antonio]] and challenged them to finish school and go to college. He offered a $2,000 scholarship to everyone who did. In 1998, proving even better than his word, Robinson awarded $8,000 to each of those students who had completed his challenge. In perhaps his greatest civic and charitable achievement, David and his wife, Valerie, founded the [[Carver Academy]] in San Antonio, which opened its doors in September 2001. To date, the Robinsons have donated more than $11&nbsp;million to the school.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS169948+12-Feb-2008+BW20080212?symbol=JPM.N |title=David Robinson, Chase Invest Sweat, Equity to Rebuild New Orleans One House at a... &#124; Reuters |publisher=Uk.reuters.com |date=February 12, 2008 |accessdate=August 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090112052026/http://uk.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS169948+12-Feb-2008+BW20080212?symbol=JPM.N |archivedate=January 12, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2003, in recognition of his outstanding contributions to charity, the NBA renamed its award for outstanding charitable efforts in honor of Robinson. Winners of the NBA's Community Assist Award receive the ''David Robinson Plaque'', with the inscription \"Following the standard set by NBA Legend David Robinson who improved the community piece by piece.\" The award is given out monthly by the league to recognize players for their charitable efforts. Robinson is also the recipient of the [[William E. Simon Prize for Philanthropic Leadership]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philanthropyroundtable.org/404-page|title=404 Page|website=Philanthropy Roundtable}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philanthropyroundtable.org/404-page|title=404 Page|website=Philanthropy Roundtable}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, in recognition of his philanthropic efforts with the Carver Academy, Robinson received the Children's Champion Award from the charitable organization [[Children's Hunger Fund]].<ref>Harlan, Tim. (October 3, 2010). [http://whatsupusana.com/2010/10/chf-childrens-champion-award-banquet-set-for-oct-9/ \"CHF Children's Champion Award Banquet Set for Oct. 9\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511191959/http://whatsupusana.com/2010/10/chf-childrens-champion-award-banquet-set-for-oct-9/ |date=May 11, 2012 }}. Retrieved June 16, 2015.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n===NBA===\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n* [[Quadruple-double]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association top rookie scoring averages]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association career scoring leaders]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association career rebounding leaders]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association career blocks leaders]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association career free throw scoring leaders]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association career playoff blocks leaders]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association annual scoring leaders]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association annual rebounding leaders]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association season blocks leaders]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association players with most points in a game]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association players with most blocks in a game]]\n* [[List of NBA players who have spent their entire career with one franchise]]\n\n===College===\n* [[List of NCAA Division I men's basketball players with 13 or more blocks in a game]]\n* [[List of NCAA Division I men's basketball players with 2000 points and 1000 rebounds]]\n* [[List of NCAA Division I men's basketball season blocks leaders]]\n* [[List of NCAA Division I men's basketball season rebounding leaders]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|David Robinson}}\n*{{Basketballstats|nba_historical=david_robinson|bbr=r/robinda01}}\n*[http://www.nba.com/history/players/robinson_bio.html David Robinson @ NBA.com/History]\n*1987 [https://web.archive.org/web/20080611112656/http://www.oscarrobertsontrophy.org/content/view/14/17/ Oscar Robertson Trophy]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100613145620/http://www.admiralcenter.org/ Admiral Center]\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{United States Squad 1986 FIBA World Championship}}\n{{United States squad 1986 Goodwill Games}}\n{{United States Men Basketball Squad 1987 Pan American Games}}\n{{Footer 1988 Olympic Bronze Medalists Basketball Men}}\n{{United States squad 1992 FIBA Americas Championship}}\n{{Footer 1992 Olympic Champions Basketball Men}}\n{{Footer 1996 Olympic Champions Basketball Men}}\n{{1987 NBA Draft}}\n{{NBA NumberOne Draft Picks}}\n{{USA Basketball Male Athlete of the Year}}\n{{San Antonio Spurs 1998\u201399 NBA champions}}\n{{San Antonio Spurs 2002\u201303 NBA champions}}\n{{Basketball Hall of Fame}}\n{{2009 Basketball HOF}}\n{{FIBA Hall of Fame}}\n{{NBA50}}\n{{NBA MVP's}}\n{{NBA Defensive Players of the Year}}\n{{NBA Rookies of the Year}}\n{{NBA Sportsmanship Award Winners}}\n{{J. Walter Kennedy Citizenship Award}}\n{{IBM Award}}\n{{NBA scoring leaders}}\n{{NBA rebounding leaders}}\n{{NBA blocks leaders}}\n{{SI Sportsman of the Year}}\n{{Associated Press College Basketball Player of the Year}}\n{{Naismith Player of the Year men}}\n{{Wooden Player of the Year men}}\n{{Oscar Robertson Trophy}}\n{{Adolph Rupp Trophy}}\n{{NABC Player of the Year}}\n{{UPI College Basketball Player of the Year}}\n{{Sporting News College Men's Basketball Player of the Year}}\n{{1986 NCAA Men's Basketball Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{1987 NCAA Men's Basketball Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{NCAA Division I men's basketball blocks champion}}\n{{NCAA Division I men's basketball rebounding champion}}\n{{Colonial Athletic Association Men's Basketball Player of the Year navbox}}\n{{Coach Wooden \"Keys to Life\" Award}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robinson, David}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:African-American Christians]]\n[[Category:All-American college men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American Christians]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Florida]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1987 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1992 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Centers (basketball)]]\n[[Category:FIBA Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:FIBA World Championship-winning players]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1992 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association All-Stars]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association players with retired numbers]]\n[[Category:Navy Midshipmen men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for the United States in basketball]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for the United States in basketball]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in basketball]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Key West, Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Manassas, Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Woodbridge, Virginia]]\n[[Category:San Antonio Spurs draft picks]]\n[[Category:San Antonio Spurs players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Antonio]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Virginia Beach, Virginia]]\n[[Category:United States men's national basketball team players]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:University of the Incarnate Word alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Bagumba", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:NICKNAME", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Robinson"}
{"title_page": "Chinese aircraft carrier programme", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date= March 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\nThe '''Chinese aircraft carrier programme''' is the development, production and operation of aircraft carriers by [[China]], primarily driven by the [[People's Liberation Army Navy]] (PLAN). China has had ambitions to operate aircraft carriers since the 1970s, but at that time had never owned or operated an aircraft carrier before. Since 1985, China has acquired four retired aircraft carriers for study: the Australian {{HMAS|Melbourne|R21|6}} and the ex-[[Soviet]] carriers {{ship|Soviet aircraft carrier|Minsk||2}}, {{ship|Soviet aircraft carrier|Kiev||2}} and {{ship|Soviet aircraft carrier|Varyag||2}}. The ''Varyag'' later underwent an extensive refit to be converted into the ''Liaoning'', China's first operational aircraft carrier, which also served as a basis for China's subsequent design iterations. {{as of|2018}}, the PLAN has two combat-ready aircraft carriers, the {{ship|Chinese aircraft carrier|Liaoning||2}} and {{ship|Chinese aircraft carrier|Shandong||2}}, with the third under construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.defensenews.com/naval/2018/01/23/no-slowdown-for-chinas-navy-aspirations/|title=No slowdown for China's Navy aspirations|date=23 January 2018}}</ref> It is projected that China may possess five or six aircraft carriers by the 2030s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iiss.org/blogs/military-balance/2018/06/china-carrier-aviation-development|title=China's carrier-aviation developments: making a difference|website=IISS}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early ambitions ===\nSince the 1970s, the PLAN has expressed interest in operating an [[aircraft carrier]] as part of its [[blue-water navy|blue water]] aspirations.<ref name=\"chinadaily\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2009-03/23/content_7607571.htm|title=Japan defense minister's China visit a sign of warming relations|author1=Wang Jianfen|author2=Nie Ligao|date=23 March 2009|publisher=Chinadaily.com.cn|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101082200/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2009-03/23/content_7607571.htm|archive-date=1 January 2018|access-date=10 September 2018}}</ref> The first official plan of [[People's Liberation Army Navy|PLAN]] aircraft carrier development dated back on 31 March 1987 when the [[Commission of Science, Technology and Industry for National Defense]] approved the plan on the aircraft carrier and the next generation [[nuclear submarine]] for PLAN advocated and submitted by the then commander-in-chief of PLAN, [[Liu Huaqing]]. The original plan was to be progressed in stages, with basic research to be completed by the end of the [[Five-Year Plans of China#The Seventh Five-Year Plan, 1986-1990|7th 5-year plan]], and development of the platform and aircraft to be completed by the end of the [[Five-Year Plans of China#The Eighth Five-Year Plan, 1991-1995|8th 5-year plan]]. By 2000, construction was to begin when ordered.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\nTo prepare the commanders needed for the future aircraft carriers, the [[Central Military Commission (People's Republic of China)|Central Military Commission]] approved the program of training jet fighter pilots to be future captains in May 1987, and the Guangzhou Naval Academy ({{zh|s=\u5e7f\u5dde\u8230\u8247\u5b66\u9662|hp=Gu\u01cengzh\u014du ji\u00e0nt\u01d0ng xu\u00e9yu\u00e0n}}) was selected as the site.<ref name=\"nwrc_winter2004_china_ambitions\">{{Cite journal|last1=Storey|first1=Ian|last2=Ji|first2=You|date=Winter 2004|title=China's Aircraft Carrier Ambitions: Seeking Truth from Rumors|url=http://www.nwc.navy.mil/press/Review/2004/Winter/art6-w04.htm|url-status=dead|journal=[[Naval War College Review]]|volume=57|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061212225857/http://www.nwc.navy.mil/press/Review/2004/Winter/art6-w04.htm|archivedate=12 December 2006|accessdate=30 May 2015|number=1}}</ref>\n\nHowever, [[Liu Huaqing]]'s plan proved to be too ambitious as the domestic Chinese industry at the time could not meet the goal demanded by the plan. As a result, the plan was drastically scaled back to basic research level and the date for an aircraft carrier entering PLAN service was postponed and eventually put on hold. In the meantime, pilot candidates for warship captain training was also altered, with candidates switched to ship-borne helicopter pilots, because it was considered that naval helicopter pilots with much more ship-borne aviation experience would be better prepared than the land-based jet fighter pilots who lack ship-borne aviation experience.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\n=== Acquisition of HMAS ''Melbourne'' ===\nChina acquired the [[Royal Australian Navy|Royal Australian Navy's]] decommissioned aircraft carrier {{HMAS|Melbourne|R21|6}} in February 1985, when it was sold to the China United Shipbuilding Company to be towed to China and broken up for scrap.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|last=Hobbs|first=Commander David|date=October 2007|title=HMAS ''Melbourne'' (II) \u2013 25 Years On|journal=The Navy|volume=69|issue=4|pages=5\u20139|issn=1322-6231}}</ref> Prior to the ship's departure for China, the RAN stripped ''Melbourne'' of all electronic equipment and weapons, and welded her rudders into a fixed position so that she could not be reactivated. However, her steam catapult, arresting equipment and mirror landing system were not removed. At this time, few western experts expected that the Chinese Government would attempt to develop aircraft carriers in the future.<ref name=\"Hemmingsen14\">{{cite journal|last=Hemmingsen|first=Torbj\u00f8rg|date=June 2012|title=PLAN for action: New dawn for Chinese Naval Aviation|journal=Jane's Navy International|issn=2048-3457}}</ref> After an eventful journey, ''Melbourne'' finally arrived in China on 13 June.<ref name=\"Lind304\">{{Cite book|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/18714742|title=The Royal Australian Navy \u2013 Historic Naval Events Year by Year|last=Lind|first=Lew|publisher=Reed Books|year=1986|isbn=0-7301-0071-5|edition=2nd|location=Frenchs Forest, NSW|oclc=16922225|ref=harv|origyear=1982}}</ref>\n\nThe ship was not scrapped immediately; instead she was studied by Chinese naval architects and engineers.<ref name=\"Storey79\">{{cite journal|last=Storey|first=Ian|author2=Ji, You|date=Winter 2004|title=China's aircraft carrier ambitions: seeking truth from rumours|url=http://www.usnwc.edu/getattachment/ffc60b3e-d2e6-4142-9b71-6dfa247051f2/China-s-Aircraft-Carrier-Ambitions--Seeking-Truth-|url-status=dead|journal=[[Naval War College Review]]|volume=57|issue=1|pages=77\u201393|issn=0028-1484|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614023207/http://www.usnwc.edu/getattachment/ffc60b3e-d2e6-4142-9b71-6dfa247051f2/China-s-Aircraft-Carrier-Ambitions--Seeking-Truth-|archivedate=14 June 2010|accessdate=25 October 2009}}</ref> It is unclear whether the [[People's Liberation Army Navy]] (PLAN) orchestrated the acquisition of ''Melbourne'' or simply took advantage of the situation; Rear Admiral [[Zhang Zhaozhong (military official)|Zhang Zhaozhong]], a staff member at the [[PLA National Defense University|National Defence College]], has stated that the Navy was unaware of the purchase until ''Melbourne'' first arrived at Guangzhou.<ref name=\"Hemmingsen14\" /> ''Melbourne'' was the largest warship any of the Chinese experts had seen, and they were surprised by the amount of equipment which was still in place. The PLAN subsequently arranged for the ship's flight deck and all the equipment associated with flying operations to be removed so that they could be studied in depth.<ref name=\"Hemmingsen14\" /> Reports have circulated that either a replica of the flight deck, or the deck itself, was used for clandestine training of [[People's Liberation Army Navy]] pilots in carrier flight operations.<ref name=\"Storey79\" />\n\nChinese engineers reverse-engineered a land-based replica of the steam catapult and landing system from that of {{HMAS|Melbourne|R21|6}}, and a [[Shenyang J-8#Variants|J-8IIG]] was used to conduct take-off and landing trials on the land-based flight deck in April 1987, which was not finally confirmed officially until 27 years later in April 2014 by [[CCTV-13]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xinruijunshi.com/sjzb/20140422/88317.shtml|title=J-8IIG|accessdate=22 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127155155/http://www.xinruijunshi.com/sjzb/20140422/88317.shtml|archive-date=27 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=November 2016}} Both the take-off and landing were conducted on the same day, and the test pilot was [[PLANAF]] pilot Li Guoqiang (\u674e\u56fd\u5f3a).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xinruijunshi.com/sjzb/20140422/88354.shtml|title=J-8IIG trials|accessdate=22 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127155156/http://www.xinruijunshi.com/sjzb/20140422/88354.shtml|archive-date=27 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=November 2016}} The experience gained would be later applied to the development of the [[Shenyang J-15]].<ref name=\"J-15\">{{cite web|url=http://epaper.syd.com.cn/sywb/html/2013-11/07/content_956826.htm|title=Knowledge gained from J-8 used on J-15|accessdate=7 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127155153/http://epaper.syd.com.cn/sywb/html/2013-11/07/content_956826.htm|archive-date=27 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{irrelevant citation|date=November 2016|reason=HMAS Melbourne is not mentioned in source.}}\n\nIt has also been claimed that the Royal Australian Navy received and \"politely rejected\" a request from the PLAN for blueprints of the ship's steam catapult.<ref name=\"Hemmingsen14\" /> The carrier was not dismantled for many years; according to some rumours she was not completely broken up until 2002.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Other acquisition attempts ===\nChina also negotiated with Spain in an effort purchase the blueprints for proposed conventional take off/landing ships from [[Navantia|''Empresa Nacional Bazan'']], specifically 23,000-ton SAC-200 and 25,000-ton SAC-220 designs. Negotiations started between 1995 and 1996 but did not result in any purchase. However, the Spanish firm was paid several million US dollars in consulting fees, indicating the probable transfer of some design concepts.<ref name=\"nwrc_winter2004_china_ambitions\" />\n\nChina acquired the former Soviet {{Sclass-|Kiev|aircraft carrier|1}}s {{ship|Soviet aircraft carrier|Minsk||2}} in 1995 and {{ship|Soviet aircraft carrier|Kiev||2}} in 2000. ''Minsk'', along with its sister ship {{ship|Soviet aircraft carrier|Novorossiysk||2}}, were initially sold to South Korea in 1995 to be scrapped,<ref name=\"Storey79\" /> but due to objections from environmentalists,<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1999/01/25/chinas-first-aircraft-carrier-anchors-in-fun-zone/66c78e76-fe65-4436-b4f0-447b66d28829/|title=China's First Aircraft Carrier Anchors in 'Fun Zone'|last1=Laris|first1=Michael|date=25 January 1999|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> ''Minsk'' was resold to China in 1998 to be broken up there instead.<ref name=\"Storey79\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> ''Kiev'', likewise, was sold to China in 2000 by Russia with a contractual requirement for it to be scrapped.<ref name=\"Storey79\" /> However, neither ship was dismantled and both were instead converted into tourist attractions, with ''Minsk'' turned into a theme park<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.rian.ru/world/20060531/48857033.html|title=Former Soviet aircraft carrier sold in China for $16mln|date=31 May 2006|publisher=Sputnik International|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.szdaily.com/content/2016-04/04/content_12991857.htm|title=Soviet-era ship leaves Shenzhen|last1=Han|first1=Ximin|date=4 April 2016|accessdate=16 April 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427201625/http://www1.szdaily.com/content/2016-04/04/content_12991857.htm|archivedate=27 April 2016|url-status=dead|publisher=[[Shenzhen Daily]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://js.qq.com/a/20160404/017826.htm|title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u9996\u8258\u822a\u6bcd\u660e\u65af\u514b\u53f7\u8d77\u951a\u9a76\u5411\u6c5f\u82cf 4\u6708\u4e0b\u65ec\u62b5\u8fbe|date=4 April 2016|accessdate=4 April 2016|publisher=\u626c\u5b50\u665a\u62a5\u7f51}}</ref> and ''Kiev'' a luxury hotel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2024729/China-launches-second-aircraft-carrier-9-6m-refit--luxury-hotel.html?ITO=1490|title=China launches second aircraft carrier after a \u00a39.6m refit... as a luxury hotel|date=11 August 2011|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/aug/10/china-aircraft-carrier-luxury-hotel|title=China launches second aircraft carrier \u2013 as luxury hotel|last=Branigan|first=Tania|date=10 August 2011|work=The Guardian|accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, China attempted to purchase the retired French aircraft carrier {{ship|French aircraft carrier|Clemenceau|R98|2}}, but negotiations between China and France failed.<ref name=\"nwrc_winter2004_china_ambitions\" />\n\n===''Liaoning'' (Type 001)===\n{{anchor|Liaoning|Type 001}}\n[[File:USNWC Varyag01.jpg|thumb|''Liaoning'' before refurbishment]]{{Main|Chinese aircraft carrier Liaoning}}The 67,500&nbsp;ton ex-[[Chinese aircraft carrier Liaoning|Soviet aircraft carrier ''Varyag'']] ({{sclass-|Kuznetsov|aircraft carrier|4}}), which was only 68% completed and floating in [[Ukraine]], was purchased through a private [[Macau]] tourist venture in 1998. Following [[Chinese aircraft carrier Liaoning#Transfer to China|her troublesome tow to Dalian shipyard]], the carrier underwent a long refit. ''Varyag'' had been stripped of any military equipment as well as her propulsion systems prior to being put up for sale. In 2007 there were news reports that she was being fitted out to enter service.<ref name=\"asahi\">{{citation|last=Minemura|first=Kenji|title=China to start construction of 1st aircraft carriers next year|date=31 December 2008|url=http://www.asahi.com/english/Herald-asahi/TKY200812310046.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090526192305/http://www.asahi.com/english/Herald-asahi/TKY200812310046.html|publisher=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|accessdate=30 May 2015|archivedate=26 May 2009}}</ref><ref name=janes>{{cite magazine|first=Jon |last=Rosamond |title=China completes joint exercise with UK aircraft carrier |magazine=Jane's Navy International |date=November 2007 |pages=6}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, [[People's Liberation Army]] Chief of the General Staff [[Chen Bingde]] confirmed that China was constructing at least one aircraft carrier.<ref name=\"Under Construction 2011\">{{cite news|title=PLA Chief Confirms Vessel Is 'Under Construction'|date=8 June 2011|work=[[Global Times]]}}</ref> On 10 August 2011, it was announced that the refurbishment of ''Varyag'' was complete, and that it was undergoing sea trials.<ref name=FT20110810>{{cite web | first = Kathrin | last = Hille | date = 10 August 2011 | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/6b20cdce-c300-11e0-8cc7-00144feabdc0.html | title = China's first aircraft carrier takes to the sea | work = The Financial Times |accessdate=30 May 2015}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=CBS20110810>{{cite news | url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/story/2011/08/10/china-aircraft-carrier.html | title = China's first aircraft carrier begins sea trials | date = 10 August 2011 |work = CBC News |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:J-15 03.jpg|thumb|J-15 Flying Shark]]\nOn 14 December 2011, DigitalGlobe, an American Satellite imaging company, announced that while scouring through pictures taken 8 December, it had discovered the retrofitted ''Varyag'' undergoing trials, DigitalGlobe further stated that their images captured the ship in the Yellow Sea where it operated for 5 days.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/dec/15/us-satellite-china-aircraft-carrier?newsfeed=true | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=US satellite snaps China's first aircraft carrier at sea | date=15 December 2011 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, it was announced that this carrier would be named ''Liaoning'', after [[Liaoning Province]] of China. In September 2012, China's first aircraft carrier, ''Liaoning'', was commissioned.<ref name=\"ChinaPower\"/> On 23 September 2012, ''Liaoning'' was handed over to the People's Liberation Army Navy, but was not yet in active service.<ref name=\"WFW-INC-2012-01\">{{cite news|title=China navy takes delivery of first aircraft carrier|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/asia/story/china-navy-takes-delivery-first-aircraft-carrier-report-20120923|accessdate=30 May 2015 |date=23 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, the first landing was successfully conducted on ''Liaoning'' with [[Shenyang J-15]].<ref name=\"xinhuanetmil\">{{cite news| url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/mil/2012-11/25/c_123998020.htm | location=\u5317\u4eac | work=\u65b0\u534e\u7f51 |script-title=zh:\u6211\u822a\u7a7a\u6bcd\u8230\u987a\u5229\u8fdb\u884c\u6b7c\u201415\u98de\u673a\u8d77\u964d\u98de\u884c\u8bad\u7ec3 | date=25 November 2012 |accessdate=30 May 2015 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nFour years later, in November 2016, it was reported that ''Liaoning'' was combat ready. China has confirmed that it is constructing a second carrier that will be built entirely with indigenous Chinese designs. Similar to ''Liaoning'', China's second carrier will also use a [[Ski-jump (aviation)|ski jump]] for takeoff.<ref name=\"ChinaPower\">{{cite web|url=http://chinapower.csis.org/aircraft-carrier/|title=How does China's first aircraft carrier stack up?|author=ChinaPower|date=9 December 2015|publisher=Center for Strategic and International Studies}}</ref>\n\n==Current status==\nIn mid-2007, Chinese domestic sources revealed that China had purchased a total of four sets of aircraft carrier landing systems from Russia<ref name=\"abcnews\">{{citation |first=Christopher |last=Bodeen |title=Speculation Grows on China Aircraft Carrier Plans |url=http://a.abcnews.com/International/wireStory?id=7020155 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090507232348/http://a.abcnews.com/International/wireStory?id=7020155 |agency=Associated Press |work=abcnews |date= 6 March 2009 |archivedate=7 May 2009 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref> and this was confirmed by Russian manufacturers. However, experts disagreed on the usage of these systems: while some have claimed that it is a clear evidence of the construction of an aircraft carrier, others claim these systems are used to train pilots for a future ship. In August, 2008, Mr. Huang Qiang ({{lang|zh-hans-CN|\u9ec4\u5f3a}}), the speaker of the [[Commission of Science, Technology and Industry for National Defense]] announced to the public at a news conference that China had mastered all of the technologies for an aircraft carrier, and would build aircraft carriers in the future when the time was deemed right.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} Reports initially claimed that up to two carriers based on the ''Varyag'' would be started by 2015.<ref name=\"asahi\" />\n\nAccording to the [[Nippon News Network]] (NNN), research and development on the planned carriers is being carried out at a military research facility in [[Wuhan]].  NNN states that the actual carriers will be constructed at [[Jiangnan Shipyard]] in [[Shanghai]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=auto&tl=en&u=http://www.news24.jp/articles/2010/01/10/10151306.html|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com}}</ref>  ''Kanwa Intelligence Review'' reports that the second carrier to be constructed will likely be assigned to [[Qingdao]].<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Kanwa Intelligence Review |title=Long-Range SAMS Deployed in Qingdao |date=10 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a February 2011 report in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', the Chinese military has constructed a concrete aircraft carrier flight deck to use for training carrier pilots and carrier operations personnel.  The deck was constructed on top of a government building near Wuhan (Wuhan Technical College of Communication campus next to Huangjiahu).<ref>{{citation |last=Harding |first=Thomas |title=Concrete Evidence of China's Naval Ambitions |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/8307646/Concrete-evidence-of-Chinas-naval-ambitions.html |work=The Daily Telegraph|date=7 February 2011 |location=London |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 June 2011, [[People's Liberation Army]] Chief of the General Staff [[Chen Bingde]] confirmed that China was constructing its own aircraft carrier. He stated he would provide no further details until it was complete.<ref name=\"Under Construction 2011\"/>\n\nOn 30 July 2011, a senior researcher of the [[Academy of Military Science (People's Republic of China)|Academy of Military Sciences]] said China needed at least three aircraft carriers. \"If we consider our neighbours, India will have three aircraft carriers by 2014 and Japan will have three carriers by 2014, so I think the number (for China) should not be less than three so we can defend our rights and our maritime interests effectively.\" General Luo Yuan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spacewar.com/reports/China_needs_at_least_three_aircraft_carriers_general_999.html |title=China needs at least three aircraft carriers: general |publisher=Spacewar |date=30 July 2011 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref> In July 2011, a Chinese official announced that two aircraft carriers were being built at the Jiangnan Shipyard in Shanghai.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gertz |first=Bill |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/aug/1/china-begins-to-build-its-own-aircraft-carrier/?page=all |title=China begins to build its own aircraft carrier |work=[[Washington Times]] |date=2 August 2011 |pages=1 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/27/us-china-carrier-idUSTRE76Q1X120110727 |title=China boosts naval power with carrier program: sources |last1=Blanchard |first1=Ben |last2=Lim |first2=Benjamin |date=27 July 2011 |accessdate=30 May 2015 |work= [[Reuters]]}}</ref> On 21 May 2012, Taiwan's intelligence chief Tsai Teh-sheng told the Legislative Yuan that the PLA Navy plans to build two carriers, scheduled to start construction in 2013 and 2015 and launch in 2020 and 2022 respectively.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[Channel NewsAsia]] |title=Taiwan Says China To Build Two Aircraft Carriers |date=22 May 2012}}</ref> On 24 April 2013, Chinese Rear Admiral Song Xue confirmed that China will build more carriers and these will be larger and will carry more fighter-planes than ''Liaoning''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/04/24/us-china-navy-carrier-idUSBRE93N00Q20130424 | work=Reuters | first=Pete | last=Sweeney | title=China to build second, larger carrier: report | date=24 April 2013 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Type 002 ===\n[[File:\u505c\u6cca\u4e8e\u5927\u8fde\u6e2f\u7684001A.jpg|thumb|The Type 002 aircraft carrier in 2017]]\n{{Main|Chinese aircraft carrier Shandong}}\n\nIn December 2013, China's Central Military Commission told Duowei News it planned to commission two ''Liaoning''-pattern aircraft carriers by 2020, designated as Type 001 and Type 002. Contracts have been awarded to China Shipbuilding Industry Corporation to build the two carriers. The cost is projected to be US$9 billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20131211000053&cid=1101 |title=New aircraft carriers to be built in Dalian and Shanghai: source |publisher=WantChinaTimes.com |date=11 December 2013 |accessdate=30 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418171253/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20131211000053&cid=1101 |archivedate=18 April 2015  }}</ref> A waist catapult could be fitted to one or both vessels to facilitate airborne early warning aircraft operation and air control. Presently ''Liaoning'' combines unassisted ski-jump launched aircraft with helicopters for anti-submarine and air defense operations.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} Construction began in 2013 and the ship was launched in April 2017.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\nOn 31 December 2015, a spokesman of the [[Chinese Ministry of Defense]] confirmed that China is designing and building its second aircraft carrier.<ref name=\"mod\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/politics/2015-12/31/c_1117641735.htm|title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u6b63\u5728\u81ea\u4e3b\u5f00\u5c55\u8bbe\u8ba1\u548c\u5efa\u9020\u7b2c\u4e8c\u8258\u822a\u7a7a\u6bcd\u8230|date=31 December 2015|publisher=\u65b0\u534e\u7f51}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2015-12/31/c_134968258.htm|title=China building second aircraft carrier|date=31 December 2016 |publisher=Xinhuanet}}</ref>\n\nThe 002 is a conventionally powered ski jump carrier with a displacement of around 70,000 tonnes.<ref name=chn002carrier>{{cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/asia/201702131050622615-china-aircraft-carriers/|title=China Reveals Launch Date of New Aircraft Carriers|work=Sputnik International| date=13 February 2017}}</ref> It is likely to be powered by oil-fired boilers and steam turbines, though previously there has been speculation that it could be gas-turbine propelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.janes.com/article/64097/further-progress-made-on-china-s-type-001a-carrier |title=Further progress made on China's Type 001A carrier |publisher=IHS Jane's Defence Weekly |date=26 September 2016 |accessdate=12 November 2016}}</ref> There are some evident differences from the Soviet built Liaoning.{{clarify|date=April 2017}} China's first homemade aircraft carrier, Type 002, left her home port of Dalian for her third sea trial on 28 Oct. 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/coming-soon-chinas-navy-could-eventually-have-six-aircraft-carriers-34742 | title=Coming Soon: China's Navy Could Eventually Have Six Aircraft Carriers| date=31 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Type 003 ===\n{{Main|Type 003 aircraft carrier}}\nThe third aircraft carrier, known as Type 003, is to be an entirely different design than Type 001 (''Liaoning'') and Type 002 (''Shandong''). It will have a displacement of around 85,000 tonnes.<ref name=chn002carrier/>\n\nIn 2015, media reports stated that both an EMALS and a steam-powered catapult were constructed at the Huangdicun naval base for testing; this is thought to indicate that the Type 003 class as well as future PLAN carriers could possibly be [[CATOBAR]] carriers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popsci.com/chinas-new-carrier-gets-ski-ramp |title=CHINA'S NEW CARRIER GETS A SKI RAMP |publisher=Popular Science |date=5 May 2016 |accessdate=12 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe construction of the first Type 003 class aircraft carrier started in February 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.janes.com/article/68236/china-building-third-aircraft-carrier-says-report|title=China building third aircraft carrier, says report|publisher=IHS Jane's|date=24 February 2017|accessdate=24 February 2017}}</ref> It is claimed that two ships of the class are being built in Dalian Shipyard and Jiangnan Shipyard simultaneously.<ref name=\"foxtrotalpha\" />\n\n=== Type 004 ===\n{{Main|Type 004 aircraft carrier}}\nThe Type 004 is planned to be larger than the Type 003, and also feature nuclear propulsion,<ref name=\"foxtrotalpha\">{{cite web|url=https://foxtrotalpha.jalopnik.com/inside-china-s-plan-to-build-the-second-biggest-aircraf-1828730033|title=Inside China's Plan to Build the Second-Biggest Aircraft Carrier Fleet in the World|last1=Mizokami|first1=Kyle|date=7 September 2018|website=Foxtrot Alpha|publisher=[[Jalopnik]]|access-date=2 January 2019}}</ref> which could power weapons like lasers and railguns.<ref name=\"popsci.com\">{{cite news |url=https://www.popsci.com/china-aircraft-carrier-technology |title=China's making major progress with its aircraft carrier tech |last1=Lin |first1=Jeffrey Lin |last2=Singer |first2=P.W. |date=16 August 2017 |work=[[Popular Science]] |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> It is claimed that construction started in December 2017<ref name=NewsCorpAustralia>{{cite news |url=https://www.news.com.au/technology/innovation/military/heres-what-we-know-about-chinas-newest-aircraft-carriers/news-story/7460539e54fe026976276dd4cbfaa2e1 |title=Here's what we know about China's newest aircraft carriers |last=Seidel |first=Jamie |work=[[news.com.au]] |date=23 April 2018 |access-date=19 June 2018}}</ref> at Jiangnan Shipyard.<ref name=\"NewsCorpAustralia2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/technology/innovation/military/heres-what-we-know-about-chinas-newest-aircraft-carriers/news-story/7460539e54fe026976276dd4cbfaa2e1|title=Here's what we know about China's newest aircraft carriers|last=Seidel|first=Jamie|date=23 April 2018|work=[[news.com.au]]|access-date=19 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Development of carrier-based aircraft ===\nChina initially intended to acquire Russian [[Sukhoi Su-33]] carrier-based aircraft to be operated from its aircraft carriers.<ref name=\"definddai-su33\">{{cite web|url=http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/china-to-buy-su33-carrierbased-fighters-from-russia-02806/ |title=China to Buy Su-33 Carrier-Based Fighters from Russia? |publisher=Defenseindustrydaily.com |date=26 March 2009 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref> However, China later developed the [[Shenyang J-15]] as a derivative of the Su-33,<ref name=\"New Chinese Ship-Based Fighter Progresses\">{{cite web|last=Fulghum|first=David A.|title=New Chinese Ship-Based Fighter Progresses |url=http://www.aviationweek.com/aw/generic/story.jsp?channel=defense&id=news/asd/2011/04/27/02.xml&headline=New%20Chinese%20Ship-Based%20Fighter%20Progresses&next=0 |work=Article |publisher=Aviation Week |accessdate=27 April 2011}} {{dead link|date=May 2015}}</ref> featuring Chinese technology and avionics from the [[Shenyang J-11#J-11|J-11B]] program.<ref name=\"New Chinese Ship-Based Fighter Progresses\"/>\n\nOn 25 November 2012, it was announced that at least two [[Shenyang J-15]]s had successfully landed on ''Liaoning''.<ref name=\"xinhuanetmil\"/><ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.3news.co.nz/China-lands-first-fighter-jet-on-aircraft-carrier/tabid/417/articleID/278075/Default.aspx | work= 3 News NZ | title= China lands first fighter jet on aircraft carrier | agency= Associated Press | date= 26 November 2012 | accessdate= 30 May 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131214054855/http://www.3news.co.nz/China-lands-first-fighter-jet-on-aircraft-carrier/tabid/417/articleID/278075/Default.aspx | archive-date= 14 December 2013 | url-status= dead }}</ref> The pilot credited with having achieved the first landing was Dai Mingmeng ({{lang|zh-hans-CN|\u6234\u660e\u76df}}).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://zjdaily.zjol.com.cn/qjwb/html/2012-11/24/content_1875914.htm?div=-1 | location=\u676d\u5dde | work=\u94b1\u6c5f\u665a\u62a5 |script-title=zh:\u6234\u660e\u76df\uff1a\u7740\u8230\u6210\u529f\u9996\u98de\u7b2c\u4e00\u4eba |language=zh | date=24 November 2012 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref> According to Chinese media reports, the J-15 cannot take off from ''Liaoning'' with a full weapons and fuel load exceeding 12 tons, being unable to get off the carrier's ski jump ramp.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.defensenews.com/article/20130928/DEFREG/309280009/Chinese-Media-Takes-Aim-J-15-Fighter |title=Chinese Media Takes Aim at J-15 Fighter |last=Minnick |first=Wendell |work=Defense News |date=28 September 2013 |accessdate=21 July 2015 |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20150810120751/http://archive.defensenews.com/article/20130928/DEFREG/309280009/Chinese-Media-Takes-Aim-J-15-Fighter |archive-date=10 August 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The [[Shenyang J-31]] is a fifth generation fighter aircraft being developed by China that may in future be adopted for carrier use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defenseworld.net/news/23981/Chinese_Aircraft_Maker_Issues_RFP_for_Stealth_Aircraft___s_Target_Detection_Systems|title=Chinese Aircraft Maker Issues RFP for Stealth Aircraft's Target Detection Systems|website=www.defenseworld.net}}</ref>\n\nThere are unconfirmed reports of a J-15A catapult compatible fighter being tested on an Electromagnetic (EMALS type) catapult. This is thought to likely have occurred at the Huangdicun facility.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://plarealtalk.com/2016/11/09/chinese-navy-catapult-and-j-15a/ |accessdate=12 November 2016|title=Chinese Navy catapult and J-15A|date=9 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe South China Morning Post reported on 6 July 2018 that China is developing a variant of the FC-31 as an alternate carrier operational jet.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy-defence/article/2153803/china-working-new-fighter-jet-aircraft-carriers-replace/ |accessdate=6 July 2018|title=China's navy scrambles to replace troubled J-15 carrier fighter jet|date=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== List of carriers ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Hull number\n! Name\n! Class\n! Builder\n! Launched\n! Commissioned\n! Home port\n! Status\n|-\n| 16\n| \u8fbd\u5b81 <br/>{{ship|Chinese aircraft carrier|Liaoning||2}}\n| [[Type 001 aircraft carrier|Type 001]]\n| [[Black Sea Shipyard|Mykolaiv Shipyard]] (Hull) <br/>[[Dalian Shipbuilding Industry Company|Dalian Shipyard]] (Refit)\n| December 1988\n| September 2012<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/chinas-first-aircraft-carrier-the-liaoning/2012/09/25/06cd105c-0716-11e2-a10c-fa5a255a9258_gallery.html | title=China's first aircraft carrier, the Liaoning}}</ref>\n| [[Jianggezhuang Naval Base]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://militarymachine.com/active-aircraft-carriers/16/ |title=Here Is Every One of the Active Aircraft Carriers in the World |last1=Ritsick |first1=Colin |date=19 August 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |website=militarymachine.com}}</ref>\n| Active<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/military/201904261074501982-PLAN-Declares-Chinese-Carrier-Liaoning-Combat-Ship/|title=People's Liberation Army-Navy Declares Chinese Carrier Liaoning a 'Combat Ship'|website=sputniknews.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| 17\n| \u5c71\u4e1c <br/>{{ship|Chinese aircraft carrier|Shandong||2}}\n| [[Type 002 aircraft carrier|Type 002]]\n| Dalian Shipyard\n| April 2017\n| December 2019<ref name=\"guancha.cn\">{{cite web | url=https://www.guancha.cn/military-affairs/2019_12_17_528689.shtml | title=\u9996\u8258\u56fd\u4ea7\u822a\u6bcd\u5c71\u4e1c\u8230\u4ea4\u4ed8\u6d77\u519b\uff0c\u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73\u51fa\u5e2d\u4ea4\u63a5\u5165\u5217\u4eea\u5f0f| date=17 December 2019}}</ref> \n| \n| Active\n|-\n| ''tbd''\n| ''tbd''\n| [[Type 003 aircraft carrier|Type 003]]\n| [[Jiangnan Shipyard]]\n| Estimated 2020\n| Estimated 2023\n| \n| Under construction<ref name=\"foxtrotalpha\" />\n|-\n| ''tbd''\n| ''tbd''\n| [[Type 004 aircraft carrier|Type 004]]\n| ''tbd''\n| Mid 2020s\n| Late 2020s\n| \n| Under construction<ref name=\"foxtrotalpha\" />\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*{{ship|Soviet aircraft carrier|Ulyanovsk}}\n*[[List of aircraft carriers in service]]\n*[[DF-21D]] \u2013 Chinese [[anti-ship ballistic missile]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/china/cv.htm China / Aircraft Carrier Project], GlobalSecurity.org\n* Rick Joe, [https://thediplomat.com/2019/06/a-mid-2019-guide-to-chinese-aircraft-carriers/ A Mid-2019 Guide to Chinese Aircraft Carriers: What is the future trajectory of the Chinese People\u2019s Liberation Army Navy carrier program?], \"The Diplomat,\" June 18, 2019. Varying use of \"\u201c001A\u201d and \u201c002\u201d designations\n\n{{Ship classes of the Chinese Navy}}\n{{People's Liberation Army}}\n{{Portal bar|China|War}}\n\n[[Category:Aircraft carriers of the People's Republic of China| ]]\n[[Category:Proposed aircraft carriers]]\n[[Category:Projects established in 2015]]\n[[Category:2015 in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date= March 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\nThe '''Chinese aircraft carrier programme''' is the development, production and operation of aircraft carriers by [[China]], primarily driven by the [[People's Liberation Army Navy]] (PLAN). China has had ambitions to operate aircraft carriers since the 1970s, but at that time had never owned or operated an aircraft carrier before. Since 1985, China has acquired four retired aircraft carriers for study: the Australian {{HMAS|Melbourne|R21|6}} and the ex-[[Soviet]] carriers {{ship|Soviet aircraft carrier|Minsk||2}}, {{ship|Soviet aircraft carrier|Kiev||2}} and {{ship|Soviet aircraft carrier|Varyag||2}}. The ''Varyag'' later underwent an extensive refit to be converted into the ''Liaoning'', China's first operational aircraft carrier, which also served as a basis for China's subsequent design iterations. {{as of|2018}}, the PLAN has two combat-ready aircraft carriers, the {{ship|Chinese aircraft carrier|Liaoning||2}} and {{ship|Chinese aircraft carrier|Shandong||2}}, with the third under construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.defensenews.com/naval/2018/01/23/no-slowdown-for-chinas-navy-aspirations/|title=No slowdown for China's Navy aspirations|date=23 January 2018}}</ref> It is projected that China may possess five or six aircraft carriers by the 2030s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iiss.org/blogs/military-balance/2018/06/china-carrier-aviation-development|title=China's carrier-aviation developments: making a difference|website=IISS}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early ambitions ===\nSince the 1970s, the PLAN has expressed interest in operating an [[aircraft carrier]] as part of its [[blue-water navy|blue water]] aspirations.<ref name=\"chinadaily\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2009-03/23/content_7607571.htm|title=Japan defense minister's China visit a sign of warming relations|author1=Wang Jianfen|author2=Nie Ligao|date=23 March 2009|publisher=Chinadaily.com.cn|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101082200/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2009-03/23/content_7607571.htm|archive-date=1 January 2018|access-date=10 September 2018}}</ref> The first official plan of [[People's Liberation Army Navy|PLAN]] aircraft carrier development dated back on 31 March 1987 when the [[Commission of Science, Technology and Industry for National Defense]] approved the plan on the aircraft carrier and the next generation [[nuclear submarine]] for PLAN advocated and submitted by the then commander-in-chief of PLAN, [[Liu Huaqing]]. The original plan was to be progressed in stages, with basic research to be completed by the end of the [[Five-Year Plans of China#The Seventh Five-Year Plan, 1986-1990|7th 5-year plan]], and development of the platform and aircraft to be completed by the end of the [[Five-Year Plans of China#The Eighth Five-Year Plan, 1991-1995|8th 5-year plan]]. By 2000, construction was to begin when ordered.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\nTo prepare the commanders needed for the future aircraft carriers, the [[Central Military Commission (People's Republic of China)|Central Military Commission]] approved the program of training jet fighter pilots to be future captains in May 1987, and the Guangzhou Naval Academy ({{zh|s=\u5e7f\u5dde\u8230\u8247\u5b66\u9662|hp=Gu\u01cengzh\u014du ji\u00e0nt\u01d0ng xu\u00e9yu\u00e0n}}) was selected as the site.<ref name=\"nwrc_winter2004_china_ambitions\">{{Cite journal|last1=Storey|first1=Ian|last2=Ji|first2=You|date=Winter 2004|title=China's Aircraft Carrier Ambitions: Seeking Truth from Rumors|url=http://www.nwc.navy.mil/press/Review/2004/Winter/art6-w04.htm|url-status=dead|journal=[[Naval War College Review]]|volume=57|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061212225857/http://www.nwc.navy.mil/press/Review/2004/Winter/art6-w04.htm|archivedate=12 December 2006|accessdate=30 May 2015|number=1}}</ref>\n\nHowever, [[Liu Huaqing]]'s plan proved to be too ambitious as the domestic Chinese industry at the time could not meet the goal demanded by the plan. As a result, the plan was drastically scaled back to basic research level and the date for an aircraft carrier entering PLAN service was postponed and eventually put on hold. In the meantime, pilot candidates for warship captain training was also altered, with candidates switched to ship-borne helicopter pilots, because it was considered that naval helicopter pilots with much more ship-borne aviation experience would be better prepared than the land-based jet fighter pilots who lack ship-borne aviation experience.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\n=== Acquisition of HMAS ''Melbourne'' ===\nChina acquired the [[Royal Australian Navy|Royal Australian Navy's]] decommissioned aircraft carrier {{HMAS|Melbourne|R21|6}} in February 1985, when it was sold to the China United Shipbuilding Company to be towed to China and broken up for scrap.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|last=Hobbs|first=Commander David|date=October 2007|title=HMAS ''Melbourne'' (II) \u2013 25 Years On|journal=The Navy|volume=69|issue=4|pages=5\u20139|issn=1322-6231}}</ref> Prior to the ship's departure for China, the RAN stripped ''Melbourne'' of all electronic equipment and weapons, and welded her rudders into a fixed position so that she could not be reactivated. However, her steam catapult, arresting equipment and mirror landing system were not removed. At this time, few western experts expected that the Chinese Government would attempt to develop aircraft carriers in the future.<ref name=\"Hemmingsen14\">{{cite journal|last=Hemmingsen|first=Torbj\u00f8rg|date=June 2012|title=PLAN for action: New dawn for Chinese Naval Aviation|journal=Jane's Navy International|issn=2048-3457}}</ref> After an eventful journey, ''Melbourne'' finally arrived in China on 13 June.<ref name=\"Lind304\">{{Cite book|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/18714742|title=The Royal Australian Navy \u2013 Historic Naval Events Year by Year|last=Lind|first=Lew|publisher=Reed Books|year=1986|isbn=0-7301-0071-5|edition=2nd|location=Frenchs Forest, NSW|oclc=16922225|ref=harv|origyear=1982}}</ref>\n\nThe ship was not scrapped immediately; instead she was studied by Chinese naval architects and engineers.<ref name=\"Storey79\">{{cite journal|last=Storey|first=Ian|author2=Ji, You|date=Winter 2004|title=China's aircraft carrier ambitions: seeking truth from rumours|url=http://www.usnwc.edu/getattachment/ffc60b3e-d2e6-4142-9b71-6dfa247051f2/China-s-Aircraft-Carrier-Ambitions--Seeking-Truth-|url-status=dead|journal=[[Naval War College Review]]|volume=57|issue=1|pages=77\u201393|issn=0028-1484|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614023207/http://www.usnwc.edu/getattachment/ffc60b3e-d2e6-4142-9b71-6dfa247051f2/China-s-Aircraft-Carrier-Ambitions--Seeking-Truth-|archivedate=14 June 2010|accessdate=25 October 2009}}</ref> It is unclear whether the [[People's Liberation Army Navy]] (PLAN) orchestrated the acquisition of ''Melbourne'' or simply took advantage of the situation; Rear Admiral [[Zhang Zhaozhong (military official)|Zhang Zhaozhong]], a staff member at the [[PLA National Defense University|National Defence College]], has stated that the Navy was unaware of the purchase until ''Melbourne'' first arrived at Guangzhou.<ref name=\"Hemmingsen14\" /> ''Melbourne'' was the largest warship any of the Chinese experts had seen, and they were surprised by the amount of equipment which was still in place. The PLAN subsequently arranged for the ship's flight deck and all the equipment associated with flying operations to be removed so that they could be studied in depth.<ref name=\"Hemmingsen14\" /> Reports have circulated that either a replica of the flight deck, or the deck itself, was used for clandestine training of [[People's Liberation Army Navy]] pilots in carrier flight operations.<ref name=\"Storey79\" />\n\nChinese engineers reverse-engineered a land-based replica of the steam catapult and landing system from that of {{HMAS|Melbourne|R21|6}}, and a [[Shenyang J-8#Variants|J-8IIG]] was used to conduct take-off and landing trials on the land-based flight deck in April 1987, which was not finally confirmed officially until 27 years later in April 2014 by [[CCTV-13]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xinruijunshi.com/sjzb/20140422/88317.shtml|title=J-8IIG|accessdate=22 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127155155/http://www.xinruijunshi.com/sjzb/20140422/88317.shtml|archive-date=27 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=November 2016}} Both the take-off and landing were conducted on the same day, and the test pilot was [[PLANAF]] pilot Li Guoqiang (\u674e\u56fd\u5f3a).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xinruijunshi.com/sjzb/20140422/88354.shtml|title=J-8IIG trials|accessdate=22 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127155156/http://www.xinruijunshi.com/sjzb/20140422/88354.shtml|archive-date=27 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=November 2016}} The experience gained would be later applied to the development of the [[Shenyang J-15]].<ref name=\"J-15\">{{cite web|url=http://epaper.syd.com.cn/sywb/html/2013-11/07/content_956826.htm|title=Knowledge gained from J-8 used on J-15|accessdate=7 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127155153/http://epaper.syd.com.cn/sywb/html/2013-11/07/content_956826.htm|archive-date=27 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{irrelevant citation|date=November 2016|reason=HMAS Melbourne is not mentioned in source.}}\n\nIt has also been claimed that the Royal Australian Navy received and \"politely rejected\" a request from the PLAN for blueprints of the ship's steam catapult.<ref name=\"Hemmingsen14\" /> The carrier was not dismantled for many years; according to some rumours she was not completely broken up until 2002.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Other acquisition attempts ===\nChina also negotiated with Spain in an effort purchase the blueprints for proposed conventional take off/landing ships from [[Navantia|''Empresa Nacional Bazan'']], specifically 23,000-ton SAC-200 and 25,000-ton SAC-220 designs. Negotiations started between 1995 and 1996 but did not result in any purchase. However, the Spanish firm was paid several million US dollars in consulting fees, indicating the probable transfer of some design concepts.<ref name=\"nwrc_winter2004_china_ambitions\" />\n\nChina acquired the former Soviet {{Sclass-|Kiev|aircraft carrier|1}}s {{ship|Soviet aircraft carrier|Minsk||2}} in 1995 and {{ship|Soviet aircraft carrier|Kiev||2}} in 2000. ''Minsk'', along with its sister ship {{ship|Soviet aircraft carrier|Novorossiysk||2}}, were initially sold to South Korea in 1995 to be scrapped,<ref name=\"Storey79\" /> but due to objections from environmentalists,<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1999/01/25/chinas-first-aircraft-carrier-anchors-in-fun-zone/66c78e76-fe65-4436-b4f0-447b66d28829/|title=China's First Aircraft Carrier Anchors in 'Fun Zone'|last1=Laris|first1=Michael|date=25 January 1999|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> ''Minsk'' was resold to China in 1998 to be broken up there instead.<ref name=\"Storey79\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> ''Kiev'', likewise, was sold to China in 2000 by Russia with a contractual requirement for it to be scrapped.<ref name=\"Storey79\" /> However, neither ship was dismantled and both were instead converted into tourist attractions, with ''Minsk'' turned into a theme park<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.rian.ru/world/20060531/48857033.html|title=Former Soviet aircraft carrier sold in China for $16mln|date=31 May 2006|publisher=Sputnik International|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.szdaily.com/content/2016-04/04/content_12991857.htm|title=Soviet-era ship leaves Shenzhen|last1=Han|first1=Ximin|date=4 April 2016|accessdate=16 April 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427201625/http://www1.szdaily.com/content/2016-04/04/content_12991857.htm|archivedate=27 April 2016|url-status=dead|publisher=[[Shenzhen Daily]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://js.qq.com/a/20160404/017826.htm|title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u9996\u8258\u822a\u6bcd\u660e\u65af\u514b\u53f7\u8d77\u951a\u9a76\u5411\u6c5f\u82cf 4\u6708\u4e0b\u65ec\u62b5\u8fbe|date=4 April 2016|accessdate=4 April 2016|publisher=\u626c\u5b50\u665a\u62a5\u7f51}}</ref> and ''Kiev'' a luxury hotel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2024729/China-launches-second-aircraft-carrier-9-6m-refit--luxury-hotel.html?ITO=1490|title=China launches second aircraft carrier after a \u00a39.6m refit... as a luxury hotel|date=11 August 2011|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/aug/10/china-aircraft-carrier-luxury-hotel|title=China launches second aircraft carrier \u2013 as luxury hotel|last=Branigan|first=Tania|date=10 August 2011|work=The Guardian|accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, China attempted to purchase the retired French aircraft carrier {{ship|French aircraft carrier|Clemenceau|R98|2}}, but negotiations between China and France failed.<ref name=\"nwrc_winter2004_china_ambitions\" />\n\n===''Liaoning'' (Type 001)===\n{{anchor|Liaoning|Type 001}}\n[[File:USNWC Varyag01.jpg|thumb|''Liaoning'' before refurbishment]]{{Main|Chinese aircraft carrier Liaoning}}The 67,500&nbsp;ton ex-[[Chinese aircraft carrier Liaoning|Soviet aircraft carrier ''Varyag'']] ({{sclass-|Kuznetsov|aircraft carrier|4}}), which was only 68% completed and floating in [[Ukraine]], was purchased through a private [[Macau]] tourist venture in 1998. Following [[Chinese aircraft carrier Liaoning#Transfer to China|her troublesome tow to Dalian shipyard]], the carrier underwent a long refit. ''Varyag'' had been stripped of any military equipment as well as her propulsion systems prior to being put up for sale. In 2007 there were news reports that she was being fitted out to enter service.<ref name=\"asahi\">{{citation|last=Minemura|first=Kenji|title=China to start construction of 1st aircraft carriers next year|date=31 December 2008|url=http://www.asahi.com/english/Herald-asahi/TKY200812310046.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090526192305/http://www.asahi.com/english/Herald-asahi/TKY200812310046.html|publisher=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|accessdate=30 May 2015|archivedate=26 May 2009}}</ref><ref name=janes>{{cite magazine|first=Jon |last=Rosamond |title=China completes joint exercise with UK aircraft carrier |magazine=Jane's Navy International |date=November 2007 |pages=6}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, [[People's Liberation Army]] Chief of the General Staff [[Chen Bingde]] confirmed that China was constructing at least one aircraft carrier.<ref name=\"Under Construction 2011\">{{cite news|title=PLA Chief Confirms Vessel Is 'Under Construction'|date=8 June 2011|work=[[Global Times]]}}</ref> On 10 August 2011, it was announced that the refurbishment of ''Varyag'' was complete, and that it was undergoing sea trials.<ref name=FT20110810>{{cite web | first = Kathrin | last = Hille | date = 10 August 2011 | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/6b20cdce-c300-11e0-8cc7-00144feabdc0.html | title = China's first aircraft carrier takes to the sea | work = The Financial Times |accessdate=30 May 2015}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=CBS20110810>{{cite news | url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/story/2011/08/10/china-aircraft-carrier.html | title = China's first aircraft carrier begins sea trials | date = 10 August 2011 |work = CBC News |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:J-15 03.jpg|thumb|J-15 Flying Shark]]\nOn 14 December 2011, DigitalGlobe, an American Satellite imaging company, announced that while scouring through pictures taken 8 December, it had discovered the retrofitted ''Varyag'' undergoing trials, DigitalGlobe further stated that their images captured the ship in the Yellow Sea where it operated for 5 days.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/dec/15/us-satellite-china-aircraft-carrier?newsfeed=true | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=US satellite snaps China's first aircraft carrier at sea | date=15 December 2011 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, it was announced that this carrier would be named ''Liaoning'', after [[Liaoning Province]] of China. In September 2012, China's first aircraft carrier, ''Liaoning'', was commissioned.<ref name=\"ChinaPower\"/> On 23 September 2012, ''Liaoning'' was handed over to the People's Liberation Army Navy, but was not yet in active service.<ref name=\"WFW-INC-2012-01\">{{cite news|title=China navy takes delivery of first aircraft carrier|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/asia/story/china-navy-takes-delivery-first-aircraft-carrier-report-20120923|accessdate=30 May 2015 |date=23 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, the first landing was successfully conducted on ''Liaoning'' with [[Shenyang J-15]].<ref name=\"xinhuanetmil\">{{cite news| url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/mil/2012-11/25/c_123998020.htm | location=\u5317\u4eac | work=\u65b0\u534e\u7f51 |script-title=zh:\u6211\u822a\u7a7a\u6bcd\u8230\u987a\u5229\u8fdb\u884c\u6b7c\u201415\u98de\u673a\u8d77\u964d\u98de\u884c\u8bad\u7ec3 | date=25 November 2012 |accessdate=30 May 2015 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nFour years later, in November 2016, it was reported that ''Liaoning'' was combat ready. China has confirmed that it is constructing a second carrier that will be built entirely with indigenous Chinese designs. Similar to ''Liaoning'', China's second carrier will also use a [[Ski-jump (aviation)|ski jump]] for takeoff.<ref name=\"ChinaPower\">{{cite web|url=http://chinapower.csis.org/aircraft-carrier/|title=How does China's first aircraft carrier stack up?|author=ChinaPower|date=9 December 2015|publisher=Center for Strategic and International Studies}}</ref>\n\n==Current status==\nIn mid-2007, Chinese domestic sources revealed that China had purchased a total of four sets of aircraft carrier landing systems from Russia<ref name=\"abcnews\">{{citation |first=Christopher |last=Bodeen |title=Speculation Grows on China Aircraft Carrier Plans |url=http://a.abcnews.com/International/wireStory?id=7020155 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090507232348/http://a.abcnews.com/International/wireStory?id=7020155 |agency=Associated Press |work=abcnews |date= 6 March 2009 |archivedate=7 May 2009 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref> and this was confirmed by Russian manufacturers. However, experts disagreed on the usage of these systems: while some have claimed that it is a clear evidence of the construction of an aircraft carrier, others claim these systems are used to train pilots for a future ship. In August, 2008, Mr. Huang Qiang ({{lang|zh-hans-CN|\u9ec4\u5f3a}}), the speaker of the [[Commission of Science, Technology and Industry for National Defense]] announced to the public at a news conference that China had mastered all of the technologies for an aircraft carrier, and would build aircraft carriers in the future when the time was deemed right.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} Reports initially claimed that up to two carriers based on the ''Varyag'' would be started by 2015.<ref name=\"asahi\" />\n\nAccording to the [[Nippon News Network]] (NNN), research and development on the planned carriers is being carried out at a military research facility in [[Wuhan]].  NNN states that the actual carriers will be constructed at [[Jiangnan Shipyard]] in [[Shanghai]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=auto&tl=en&u=http://www.news24.jp/articles/2010/01/10/10151306.html|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com}}</ref>  ''Kanwa Intelligence Review'' reports that the second carrier to be constructed will likely be assigned to [[Qingdao]].<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Kanwa Intelligence Review |title=Long-Range SAMS Deployed in Qingdao |date=10 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a February 2011 report in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', the Chinese military has constructed a concrete aircraft carrier flight deck to use for training carrier pilots and carrier operations personnel.  The deck was constructed on top of a government building near Wuhan (Wuhan Technical College of Communication campus next to Huangjiahu).<ref>{{citation |last=Harding |first=Thomas |title=Concrete Evidence of China's Naval Ambitions |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/8307646/Concrete-evidence-of-Chinas-naval-ambitions.html |work=The Daily Telegraph|date=7 February 2011 |location=London |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 June 2011, [[People's Liberation Army]] Chief of the General Staff [[Chen Bingde]] confirmed that China was constructing its own aircraft carrier. He stated he would provide no further details until it was complete.<ref name=\"Under Construction 2011\"/>\n\nOn 30 July 2011, a senior researcher of the [[Academy of Military Science (People's Republic of China)|Academy of Military Sciences]] said China needed at least three aircraft carriers. \"If we consider our neighbours, India will have three aircraft carriers by 2014 and Japan will have three carriers by 2014, so I think the number (for China) should not be less than three so we can defend our rights and our maritime interests effectively.\" General Luo Yuan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spacewar.com/reports/China_needs_at_least_three_aircraft_carriers_general_999.html |title=China needs at least three aircraft carriers: general |publisher=Spacewar |date=30 July 2011 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref> In July 2011, a Chinese official announced that two aircraft carriers were being built at the Jiangnan Shipyard in Shanghai.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gertz |first=Bill |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/aug/1/china-begins-to-build-its-own-aircraft-carrier/?page=all |title=China begins to build its own aircraft carrier |work=[[Washington Times]] |date=2 August 2011 |pages=1 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/27/us-china-carrier-idUSTRE76Q1X120110727 |title=China boosts naval power with carrier program: sources |last1=Blanchard |first1=Ben |last2=Lim |first2=Benjamin |date=27 July 2011 |accessdate=30 May 2015 |work= [[Reuters]]}}</ref> On 21 May 2012, Taiwan's intelligence chief Tsai Teh-sheng told the Legislative Yuan that the PLA Navy plans to build two carriers, scheduled to start construction in 2013 and 2015 and launch in 2020 and 2022 respectively.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[Channel NewsAsia]] |title=Taiwan Says China To Build Two Aircraft Carriers |date=22 May 2012}}</ref> On 24 April 2013, Chinese Rear Admiral Song Xue confirmed that China will build more carriers and these will be larger and will carry more fighter-planes than ''Liaoning''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/04/24/us-china-navy-carrier-idUSBRE93N00Q20130424 | work=Reuters | first=Pete | last=Sweeney | title=China to build second, larger carrier: report | date=24 April 2013 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Type 002 ===\n[[File:\u505c\u6cca\u4e8e\u5927\u8fde\u6e2f\u7684001A.jpg|thumb|The Type 002 aircraft carrier in 2017]]\n{{Main|Chinese aircraft carrier Shandong}}\n\nIn December 2013, China's Central Military Commission told Duowei News it planned to commission two ''Liaoning''-pattern aircraft carriers by 2020, designated as Type 001 and Type 002. Contracts have been awarded to China Shipbuilding Industry Corporation to build the two carriers. The cost is projected to be US$9 billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20131211000053&cid=1101 |title=New aircraft carriers to be built in Dalian and Shanghai: source |publisher=WantChinaTimes.com |date=11 December 2013 |accessdate=30 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418171253/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20131211000053&cid=1101 |archivedate=18 April 2015  }}</ref> A waist catapult could be fitted to one or both vessels to facilitate airborne early warning aircraft operation and air control. Presently ''Liaoning'' combines unassisted ski-jump launched aircraft with helicopters for anti-submarine and air defense operations.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} Construction began in 2013 and the ship was launched in April 2017.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\nOn 31 December 2015, a spokesman of the [[Chinese Ministry of Defense]] confirmed that China is designing and building its second aircraft carrier.<ref name=\"mod\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/politics/2015-12/31/c_1117641735.htm|title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u6b63\u5728\u81ea\u4e3b\u5f00\u5c55\u8bbe\u8ba1\u548c\u5efa\u9020\u7b2c\u4e8c\u8258\u822a\u7a7a\u6bcd\u8230|date=31 December 2015|publisher=\u65b0\u534e\u7f51}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2015-12/31/c_134968258.htm|title=China building second aircraft carrier|date=31 December 2016 |publisher=Xinhuanet}}</ref>\n\nThe 002 is a conventionally powered ski jump carrier with a displacement of around 70,000 tonnes.<ref name=chn002carrier>{{cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/asia/201702131050622615-china-aircraft-carriers/|title=China Reveals Launch Date of New Aircraft Carriers|work=Sputnik International| date=13 February 2017}}</ref> It is likely to be powered by oil-fired boilers and steam turbines, though previously there has been speculation that it could be gas-turbine propelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.janes.com/article/64097/further-progress-made-on-china-s-type-001a-carrier |title=Further progress made on China's Type 001A carrier |publisher=IHS Jane's Defence Weekly |date=26 September 2016 |accessdate=12 November 2016}}</ref> There are some evident differences from the Soviet built Liaoning.{{clarify|date=April 2017}} China's first homemade aircraft carrier, Type 002, left her home port of Dalian for her third sea trial on 28 Oct. 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/coming-soon-chinas-navy-could-eventually-have-six-aircraft-carriers-34742 | title=Coming Soon: China's Navy Could Eventually Have Six Aircraft Carriers| date=31 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Type 003 ===\n{{Main|Type 003 aircraft carrier}}\nThe third aircraft carrier, known as Type 003, is to be an entirely different design than Type 001 (''Liaoning'') and Type 002 (''Shandong''). It will have a displacement of around 85,000 tonnes.<ref name=chn002carrier/>\n\nIn 2015, media reports stated that both an EMALS and a steam-powered catapult were constructed at the Huangdicun naval base for testing; this is thought to indicate that the Type 003 class as well as future PLAN carriers could possibly be [[CATOBAR]] carriers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popsci.com/chinas-new-carrier-gets-ski-ramp |title=CHINA'S NEW CARRIER GETS A SKI RAMP |publisher=Popular Science |date=5 May 2016 |accessdate=12 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe construction of the first Type 003 class aircraft carrier started in February 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.janes.com/article/68236/china-building-third-aircraft-carrier-says-report|title=China building third aircraft carrier, says report|publisher=IHS Jane's|date=24 February 2017|accessdate=24 February 2017}}</ref> It is claimed that two ships of the class are being built in Dalian Shipyard and Jiangnan Shipyard simultaneously.<ref name=\"foxtrotalpha\" />\n\n=== Type 004 ===\n{{Main|Type 004 aircraft carrier}}\nThe Type 004 is planned to be larger than the Type 003, and also feature nuclear propulsion,<ref name=\"foxtrotalpha\">{{cite web|url=https://foxtrotalpha.jalopnik.com/inside-china-s-plan-to-build-the-second-biggest-aircraf-1828730033|title=Inside China's Plan to Build the Second-Biggest Aircraft Carrier Fleet in the World|last1=Mizokami|first1=Kyle|date=7 September 2018|website=Foxtrot Alpha|publisher=[[Jalopnik]]|access-date=2 January 2019}}</ref> which could power weapons like lasers and railguns.<ref name=\"popsci.com\">{{cite news |url=https://www.popsci.com/china-aircraft-carrier-technology |title=China's making major progress with its aircraft carrier tech |last1=Lin |first1=Jeffrey Lin |last2=Singer |first2=P.W. |date=16 August 2017 |work=[[Popular Science]] |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> It is claimed that construction started in December 2017<ref name=NewsCorpAustralia>{{cite news |url=https://www.news.com.au/technology/innovation/military/heres-what-we-know-about-chinas-newest-aircraft-carriers/news-story/7460539e54fe026976276dd4cbfaa2e1 |title=Here's what we know about China's newest aircraft carriers |last=Seidel |first=Jamie |work=[[news.com.au]] |date=23 April 2018 |access-date=19 June 2018}}</ref> at Jiangnan Shipyard.<ref name=\"NewsCorpAustralia2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/technology/innovation/military/heres-what-we-know-about-chinas-newest-aircraft-carriers/news-story/7460539e54fe026976276dd4cbfaa2e1|title=Here's what we know about China's newest aircraft carriers|last=Seidel|first=Jamie|date=23 April 2018|work=[[news.com.au]]|access-date=19 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Development of carrier-based aircraft ===\nChina initially intended to acquire Russian [[Sukhoi Su-33]] carrier-based aircraft to be operated from its aircraft carriers.<ref name=\"definddai-su33\">{{cite web|url=http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/china-to-buy-su33-carrierbased-fighters-from-russia-02806/ |title=China to Buy Su-33 Carrier-Based Fighters from Russia? |publisher=Defenseindustrydaily.com |date=26 March 2009 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref> However, China later developed the [[Shenyang J-15]] as a derivative of the Su-33,<ref name=\"New Chinese Ship-Based Fighter Progresses\">{{cite web|last=Fulghum|first=David A.|title=New Chinese Ship-Based Fighter Progresses |url=http://www.aviationweek.com/aw/generic/story.jsp?channel=defense&id=news/asd/2011/04/27/02.xml&headline=New%20Chinese%20Ship-Based%20Fighter%20Progresses&next=0 |work=Article |publisher=Aviation Week |accessdate=27 April 2011}} {{dead link|date=May 2015}}</ref> featuring Chinese technology and avionics from the [[Shenyang J-11#J-11|J-11B]] program.<ref name=\"New Chinese Ship-Based Fighter Progresses\"/>\n\nOn 25 November 2012, it was announced that at least two [[Shenyang J-15]]s had successfully landed on ''Liaoning''.<ref name=\"xinhuanetmil\"/><ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.3news.co.nz/China-lands-first-fighter-jet-on-aircraft-carrier/tabid/417/articleID/278075/Default.aspx | work= 3 News NZ | title= China lands first fighter jet on aircraft carrier | agency= Associated Press | date= 26 November 2012 | accessdate= 30 May 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131214054855/http://www.3news.co.nz/China-lands-first-fighter-jet-on-aircraft-carrier/tabid/417/articleID/278075/Default.aspx | archive-date= 14 December 2013 | url-status= dead }}</ref> The pilot credited with having achieved the first landing was Dai Mingmeng ({{lang|zh-hans-CN|\u6234\u660e\u76df}}).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://zjdaily.zjol.com.cn/qjwb/html/2012-11/24/content_1875914.htm?div=-1 | location=\u676d\u5dde | work=\u94b1\u6c5f\u665a\u62a5 |script-title=zh:\u6234\u660e\u76df\uff1a\u7740\u8230\u6210\u529f\u9996\u98de\u7b2c\u4e00\u4eba |language=zh | date=24 November 2012 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref> According to Chinese media reports, the J-15 cannot take off from ''Liaoning'' with a full weapons and fuel load exceeding 12 tons, being unable to get off the carrier's ski jump ramp.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.defensenews.com/article/20130928/DEFREG/309280009/Chinese-Media-Takes-Aim-J-15-Fighter |title=Chinese Media Takes Aim at J-15 Fighter |last=Minnick |first=Wendell |work=Defense News |date=28 September 2013 |accessdate=21 July 2015 |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20150810120751/http://archive.defensenews.com/article/20130928/DEFREG/309280009/Chinese-Media-Takes-Aim-J-15-Fighter |archive-date=10 August 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The [[Shenyang J-31]] is a fifth generation fighter aircraft being developed by China that may in future be adopted for carrier use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defenseworld.net/news/23981/Chinese_Aircraft_Maker_Issues_RFP_for_Stealth_Aircraft___s_Target_Detection_Systems|title=Chinese Aircraft Maker Issues RFP for Stealth Aircraft's Target Detection Systems|website=www.defenseworld.net}}</ref>\n\nThere are unconfirmed reports of a J-15A catapult compatible fighter being tested on an Electromagnetic (EMALS type) catapult. This is thought to likely have occurred at the Huangdicun facility.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://plarealtalk.com/2016/11/09/chinese-navy-catapult-and-j-15a/ |accessdate=12 November 2016|title=Chinese Navy catapult and J-15A|date=9 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe South China Morning Post reported on 6 July 2018 that China is developing a variant of the FC-31 as an alternate carrier operational jet.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy-defence/article/2153803/china-working-new-fighter-jet-aircraft-carriers-replace/ |accessdate=6 July 2018|title=China's navy scrambles to replace troubled J-15 carrier fighter jet|date=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== List of carriers ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Hull number\n! Name\n! Class\n! Builder\n! Launched\n! Commissioned\n! Home port\n! Status\n|-\n| 16\n| \u8fbd\u5b81 <br/>{{ship|Chinese aircraft carrier|Liaoning||2}}\n| [[Type 001 aircraft carrier|Type 001]]\n| [[Black Sea Shipyard|Mykolaiv Shipyard]] (Hull) <br/>[[Dalian Shipbuilding Industry Company|Dalian Shipyard]] (Refit)\n| December 1988\n| September 2012<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/chinas-first-aircraft-carrier-the-liaoning/2012/09/25/06cd105c-0716-11e2-a10c-fa5a255a9258_gallery.html | title=China's first aircraft carrier, the Liaoning}}</ref>\n| [[Jianggezhuang Naval Base]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://militarymachine.com/active-aircraft-carriers/16/ |title=Here Is Every One of the Active Aircraft Carriers in the World |last1=Ritsick |first1=Colin |date=19 August 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |website=militarymachine.com}}</ref>\n| Active<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/military/201904261074501982-PLAN-Declares-Chinese-Carrier-Liaoning-Combat-Ship/|title=People's Liberation Army-Navy Declares Chinese Carrier Liaoning a 'Combat Ship'|website=sputniknews.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| 17\n| \u5c71\u4e1c <br/>{{ship|Chinese aircraft carrier|Shandong||2}}\n| [[Type 002 aircraft carrier|Type 002]]\n| Dalian Shipyard\n| April 2017\n| December 2019<ref name=\"guancha.cn\">{{cite web | url=https://www.guancha.cn/military-affairs/2019_12_17_528689.shtml | title=\u9996\u8258\u56fd\u4ea7\u822a\u6bcd\u5c71\u4e1c\u8230\u4ea4\u4ed8\u6d77\u519b\uff0c\u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73\u51fa\u5e2d\u4ea4\u63a5\u5165\u5217\u4eea\u5f0f| date=17 December 2019}}</ref> \n| \n| Active\n|-\n| ''tbd''\n| ''tbd''\n| [[Type 003 aircraft carrier|Type 003]]\n| [[Jiangnan Shipyard]]\n| Estimated 2020\n| Estimated 2023\n| \n| Under construction<ref name=\"foxtrotalpha\" />\n|-\n| ''tbd''\n| ''tbd''\n| [[Type 004 aircraft carrier|Type 004]]\n| ''tbd''\n| Mid 2020's\n| Late 2020's\n| \n| Under construction<ref name=\"foxtrotalpha\" />\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*{{ship|Soviet aircraft carrier|Ulyanovsk}}\n*[[List of aircraft carriers in service]]\n*[[DF-21D]] \u2013 Chinese [[anti-ship ballistic missile]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/china/cv.htm China / Aircraft Carrier Project], GlobalSecurity.org\n* Rick Joe, [https://thediplomat.com/2019/06/a-mid-2019-guide-to-chinese-aircraft-carriers/ A Mid-2019 Guide to Chinese Aircraft Carriers: What is the future trajectory of the Chinese People\u2019s Liberation Army Navy carrier program?], \"The Diplomat,\" June 18, 2019. Varying use of \"\u201c001A\u201d and \u201c002\u201d designations\n\n{{Ship classes of the Chinese Navy}}\n{{People's Liberation Army}}\n{{Portal bar|China|War}}\n\n[[Category:Aircraft carriers of the People's Republic of China| ]]\n[[Category:Proposed aircraft carriers]]\n[[Category:Projects established in 2015]]\n[[Category:2015 in China]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_aircraft_carrier_programme"}
{"title_page": "Twin cities", "text_new": "{{short description|Two cities or urban centres that are founded in close geographic proximity and then grow into each other over time}}\n{{About|the general concept of \"twin cities\"|town governments establishing official links|Sister city|the area typically called the \"Twin Cities\" in the United States|Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul|other uses|Twin city (disambiguation){{!}}Twin city}}\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2011}}\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = vertical\n | image1    = View from Reunion Tower August 2015 13.jpg\n | width1    = 225\n | caption1  =\n | alt1      =\n | image2    = Fort Worth skyline 2019.jpg\n | width2    = 225\n | caption2  = [[Dallas]] (''above'') and [[Fort Worth]] (''below''), are twin cities forming the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]].\n | alt2      =\n}}\n'''Twin cities''' are a special case of two [[city|cities]] or urban centres that are founded in close geographic proximity and then grow into each other over time, losing most of their mutual [[buffer zone]].\n\nThere are no precise criteria for twin-cityhood, but to be considered twin cities, the cities involved have to have a similar administrative status and somewhat comparable sizes; a [[suburb]] of a much larger population center is usually not considered to form a twin city with it. For example, [[South San Francisco]] (population about 65,000) is not considered a twin city with [[San Francisco]] (population about 850,000). However, cities considered twinned by proximity do not necessarily match demographically, economically, or politically.\n\nIn many historical cases, cities that grew into each other's space lost their individual identities, and the border or barrier originally separating them became almost irrelevant. An 1873 case of twin cities merging to become a united city is [[Budapest]] in Hungary, which began as two settlements ([[Buda]] and [[Pest (city)|Pest]]) facing each other across the [[Danube]] at a strategic [[ford (crossing)|fording place]] along a trade route.  In China, the three ancient cities of [[Hankou]], [[Hanyang District|Hanyang]], and [[Wuchang District|Wuchang]], separated by the junction of the [[Yangtze]] and [[Han River (Shaanxi and Hubei)|Hanjiang]] rivers, were joined in 1927 into the single entity of [[Wuhan]].\n\nTwin cities may share an airport into whose [[IATA airport code|airport codes]] are integrated the component initials, e.g., [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth International Airport|DFW]] ([[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex|Dallas\u2013Fort Worth]]), [[Leeds Bradford Airport|LBA]] ([[Leeds]]&ndash;[[Bradford]]), [[Minneapolis-Saint Paul International Airport|MSP]] ([[Minneapolis]]&ndash;[[Saint Paul, Minnesota]]), [[Raleigh-Durham International Airport|RDU]] ([[Raleigh]] and [[Durham, NC]]), and [[Akron\u2013Canton Airport|CAK]] ([[Akron]]\u2013[[Canton, Ohio]]).\n\nIn some cases, such as [[Albury]]/[[Wodonga]] in Australia, the two cities are permanently divided by a state border, often one that strictly adheres to a geographical landmark, such as the [[Murray River]] that divides [[New South Wales]] from [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], and thus Albury from Wodonga. In other cases twin cities can be divided by an international border, but retain a cultural and historical similarity, for example [[Haparanda]] ([[Sweden]]) and [[Tornio]] ([[Finland]]), [[Leticia, Amazonas|Leticia]] ([[Colombia]]) and [[Tabatinga]] ([[Brazil]]) or [[Valga, Estonia|Valga]] ([[Estonia]]) and [[Valka]] ([[Latvia]]).\n\n== Examples ==\n[[Image:Obelisco - Plaza Internacional - Frontera de la Paz - Livramento - Rivera.jpeg|thumb|right|Cross-border example of twin cities: ''Plaza Internacional'' of the ''Frontera de la Paz''. On the left, Santana do Livramento (Brazil); on the right, Rivera (Uruguay).]]\n{{Example farm|date=November 2009}}\n\n=== Africa ===\n;[[Egypt]]\n* [[Cairo]] and [[Giza]]{{refn|Separated by the [[Nile]], each city is the respective capital of its governorate ([[Cairo Governorate|Cairo]] and [[Giza Governorate|Giza]]). The two communities are the main cities of [[Greater Cairo]]. They are respectively the most populous city and third most populous city in Egypt.|group= n}} \n* [[Sebennytos|Samannoud]], [[Gharbia Governorate]] and Minyet Samannoud, [[Dakahlia Governorate]]\n;[[Ghana]]\n*[[Sekondi-Takoradi]]\n\n=== Americas ===\n\n==== North America ====\n;[[Canada]]\n* [[Battleford, Saskatchewan|Battleford]] and [[North Battleford, Saskatchewan]] ''\"The Battlefords\"'' {{refn|Separated by the [[North Saskatchewan River]]. While the communities are commonly referred to by the collective \"The Battlefords,\" they retain distinctive identities.|group= n}} \n* [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia]] and [[Halifax (former city)|Halifax]]{{refn|Main cities of [[Metropolitan Halifax]], they are geographically separated by [[Halifax Harbour]]|group= n}} \n* [[Gatineau|Gatineau, Quebec]] and [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]]{{refn|form the [[National Capital Region (Canada)|National Capital Region]], geopolitically separated by the [[Ottawa River]]|group= n}} Also Known as the ''Ottawa-Gatineau Metropolitan Area''\n* [[Kitchener-Waterloo]], Ontario\n\n;[[United States]]\n* [[Augusta, Georgia]] and [[North Augusta, South Carolina]]\n* [[Alcoa, Tennessee|Alcoa]] and [[Maryville, Tennessee]]\n* [[Allentown, Pennsylvania|Allentown]] and [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]{{refn|group=n|Two of the three anchor cities of the [[Lehigh Valley]] in eastern Pennsylvania, an area that spills over into neighboring New Jersey.}}\n* [[Auburn, Maine|Auburn]] and [[Lewiston, Maine]]\n* [[Auburn, Alabama|Auburn]] and [[Opelika, Alabama]]\n* [[Benton Harbor, Michigan|Benton Harbor]] and [[St. Joseph, Michigan]]\n* [[Bloomington, Illinois|Bloomington]] and [[Normal, Illinois]]{{refn|See [[Bloomington\u2013Normal]].|group= n}}\n* [[Bluefield, Virginia]] and [[Bluefield, West Virginia]]{{refn|group=n|See [[Bluefield micropolitan area]].}}\n* [[Boise, Idaho|Boise]] and [[Nampa, Idaho|Nampa]], [[Idaho]]\n* [[Bossier City, Louisiana|Bossier City]] and [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]]{{refn|group=n|See [[Shreveport\u2013Bossier City metropolitan area]].}}\n* [[Bridgeport, Connecticut|Bridgeport]] and [[New Haven, Connecticut]]\n* [[Bristol, Tennessee]] and [[Bristol, Virginia]]\n* [[Bryan, Texas|Bryan]] and [[College Station, Texas]]{{refn|See [[College Station\u2013Bryan metropolitan area]].|group= n}}\n* [[Centralia, Washington|Centralia]] and [[Chehalis, Washington]]\n* [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]] and [[North Charleston, South Carolina]]\n* [[Champaign, Illinois|Champaign]] and [[Urbana, Illinois]]{{refn|[[Champaign, Illinois|Champaign]] was originally known as ''West Urbana'' but has since outgrown its neighbor. See [[Champaign\u2013Urbana metropolitan area]].|group= n}}\n* [[College Corner, Ohio]] and [[West College Corner, Indiana]]\n* [[Colorado City, Arizona]] and [[Hildale, Utah]]\n* [[Columbus, Georgia]] and [[Phenix City, Alabama]]\n* [[Conover, North Carolina|Conover]] and [[Newton, North Carolina]]\n* [[Crystal City, Missouri|Crystal City]] and [[Festus, Missouri]]\n* [[Dallas]] and [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]]{{refn|Twin cores of the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex|Metroplex]] of northern [[Texas]].|group= n}}\n* [[Dover, Ohio|Dover]] and [[New Philadelphia, Ohio]]\n* [[Duluth, Minnesota]], and [[Superior, Wisconsin]]{{refn|Nicknamed the [[Twin Ports]], these form the world's largest freshwater port.|group= n}} \n* [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]] and [[Raleigh, North Carolina]]{{refn|Two anchor cities of the three-city [[Research Triangle]] area.|group= n}}\n* [[Easton, Pennsylvania]] and [[Phillipsburg, New Jersey]]\n* [[Fargo, North Dakota]], and [[Moorhead, Minnesota]]{{refn|See [[Fargo\u2013Moorhead]].|group=n}}\n* [[Fitchburg, Massachusetts|Fitchburg]] and [[Leominster, Massachusetts]]\n* [[Fort Myers, Florida|Fort Myers]] and [[Cape Coral, Florida]